<div class=3D"maintitle"><h1>Newton=92s Method on&nbsp;TI-83/84 or&nbsp;TI-=
89</h1>
<p> Copyright =A9 2002=962025 by Stan&nbsp;Brown, <a href=3D"https://brownm=
ath.com/index.htm"><span style=3D"color:brown">BrownMath.com</span></a></p>
</div>
<!-- -->

<p class=3D"Summary" id=3D"Summary"><span class=3D"SummaryH"><strong class=
=3D"key">Summary:</strong></span>
Newton=92s Method is a
<strong class=3D"key">fast way to home in on real solutions of an equation<=
/strong>.
Your TI-83/84 or TI-89 can do
Newton=92s Method for you, and this page shows two ways.</p>

<p class=3D"brk"><img class=3D"fr" src=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti83/pic/ne=
wton1.gif" width=3D"222" height=3D"73" alt=3D"x sub n+1 equals x sub n minu=
s function value at x sub n over derivative at x sub n">
Newton=92s Method is <strong class=3D"key">iterative</strong>, meaning that=
 it uses a
process or recipe to move from each guess <i>x</i><sub><i>n</i></sub> to th=
e next
guess <i>x</i><sub><i>n</i>+1</sub>.
The recipe for Newton=92s Method is shown at right.
This recipe takes a tangent line to the curve at
<i>x</i>&nbsp;=3D <i>x</i><sub><i>n</i></sub>, finds the <i>x</i> value whe=
re that line
crosses the <i>x</i>&nbsp;axis, and uses that <i>x</i> value as the next gu=
ess
<i>x</i><sub><i>n</i>+1</sub>.
Any calculus textbook will have an illustration of the method.</p>

<p class=3D"nonbrk">What we are =93guessing=94 is a zero of a real-valued f=
unction.
If the guesses get progressively closer to the desired point, we say
that the method <strong class=3D"key">converges</strong>.
It turns out that if Newton=92s Method converges at all to a particular
zero, it <strong class=3D"key">converges rapidly</strong>, meaning that it =
takes
relatively few steps.
(See your textbook for conditions in which Newton=92s Method converges.)
</p>

<div class=3D"begdon fr"><span class=3D"nonprint"><a href=3D"https://www.pa=
ypal.com/webscr?cmd=3D_donations&amp;business=3Dstan_paypal@fastmail.fm&amp=
;item_name=3DBrownMath%20donation:%20ti83/newton.htm&amp;currency_code=3DUS=
D">Because this article helps you,<br>please click to donate!</a></span><sp=
an class=3D"onlyprint">Because this article helps you,<br>please donate at<=
br>BrownMath.com/donate.</span></div>

<p class=3D"brk">To start either method,
<strong class=3D"key">put the equation you want to solve into <i>f</i>(<i>x=
</i>)&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;0 form.</strong>
Technically Newton=92s Method finds zeroes of a function, not roots of
an equation. Therefore you would rewrite something like
<i>x</i>&nbsp;sin&#8239;<i>x</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;2 as
<i>x</i>&nbsp;sin&#8239;<i>x</i>&nbsp;&#8722;&nbsp;2&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;0.
(Remember from algebra that a zero of function <i>f</i> is the same as a
solution or root of the equation <i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;0 or an
<i>x</i>&nbsp;intercept of the graph of <i>f</i>.)

</p><h2 id=3D"YouDiff">Method 1: You Differentiate</h2>

<p class=3D"brk">To practice Newton=92s Method, let=92s find the square
root of 2, since it will be easy to check the answer.
&#8730;<span class=3D"radical">2</span> is a solution of x&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;&#=
8730;<span class=3D"radical">2</span> or
x=B2&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;2.
<span id=3D"U20201116a">(Yes, &#8722;&#8730;<span class=3D"radical">2</span=
> is a solution of
this new equation but not of the original equation. But we=92ll get the
positive root because of our choice of initial guess.)</span>

</p><p class=3D"nonbrk">To start, rewrite it in the form <i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)=
&nbsp;=3D
<i>x</i>=B2&nbsp;&#8722;&nbsp;2&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;0.=20
Then, differentiate the function: <i>f</i>&#8242;(<i>x</i>)&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;2=
<i>x</i>.</p>

<table class=3D"ti8389proc">

<tbody><tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Enter the function as Y1 and the derivati=
ve as Y2.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;Press [<code>Y=3D</code>].
<br>&nbsp;<br> In Y1, press [<code>x,T,&#952;,n</code>] [<code>x=B2</code>]=
 [<code>&#8722;</code>] [<code>2</code>].
<br>&nbsp;<br> In Y2, press [<code>2</code>] [<code>x,T,&#952;,n</code>].
Then cursor back to the =3D sign and press
[<code>ENTER</code>]. This tells the TI-83/84 not to graph the derivative
Y2.
<br><img src=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti83/pic/newton2.gif" width=3D"200" h=
eight=3D"136" alt=3D"TI-83/84 Y=3D screen"></td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;Press [<code>&#9670;</code>] [<code>Y=3D=
</code>].
<br>&nbsp;<br> In Y1, press [<code>X</code>] [<code>^</code>] [<code>2</cod=
e>] [<code>&#8722;</code>] [<code>2</code>] [<code>ENTER</code>]
<br>&nbsp;<br> In Y2, press [<code>2</code>] [<code>X</code>] [<code>ENTER<=
/code>] then [<code>&#9650;</code>] [<code>F4</code>]
to tell the TI-89 not to graph the derivative Y2.
<br><img src=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti83/pic/newton92.gif" width=3D"200" =
height=3D"127" alt=3D"TI-89 Y=3D screen"></td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">(optional) Graph the function to plan your initi=
al guess.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;Press [<code>ZOOM</code>] [<code>6</c=
ode>] for
<code>ZStandard</code> (standard zoom).</td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;Press [<code>F2</code>] [<code>6</code>]=
 for <code>ZoomStd</code>.</td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Return to the home screen.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;Press [<small><code>2nd</code>&nbsp;<=
code>MODE</code> <i>makes</i></small> <code>QUIT</code>].</td>
<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;Press [<small><code>2nd</code>&nbsp;<cod=
e>ESC</code> <i>makes</i></small> <code>QUIT</code>].</td></tr>
</tbody></table>

<p class=3D"brk">Next you=92ll set <i>x</i> to your first guess, then progr=
am the
recipe for getting the next guess. Let=92s guess 1 to start.</p>

<table class=3D"ti8389proc">

<tbody><tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Store the initial guess, 1, in x.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;Press [<code>1</code>] [<code>STO&#85=
94;</code>] [<code>x,T,&#952;,n</code>].</td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;Press [<code>1</code>] [<code>.</code>] =
[<code>STO&#8594;</code>] [<code>X</code>].
<br>The decimal point is important: it tells the TI-89 that you want
decimal approximations rather than exact numbers.</td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Since y1 is the left-hand side of the equation t=
o be solved
and y2 is the derivative, you want to subtract y1/y2 from x and store
the result in x as the next guess.
<br>&nbsp;<br> After the first iteration, you see the result is 1.5.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;[<code>x,T,&#952;,n</code>] [<code>&#=
8722;</code>]
<br>[<code>VARS</code>] [<code>&#9658;</code>] [<code>1</code>] [<code>1</c=
ode>] pastes Y1 to screen.
<br>[<code>=F7</code>] [<code>VARS</code>] [<code>&#9658;</code>] [<code>1<=
/code>] [<code>2</code>] pastes /Y2 to screen.
<br>[<code>STO&#8594;</code>] [<code>x,T,&#952;,n</code>] [<code>ENTER</cod=
e>]
computes the next guess and stores it in X.
<br><img src=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti83/pic/newton3.gif" width=3D"200" h=
eight=3D"136" alt=3D"first two iterations of Newton=92s Method"></td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp; You must supply the argument (x) to the=
 two functions.
<br>[<code>X</code>] [<code>&#8722;</code>] [<code>Y</code>] [<code>1</code=
>] [<code>(</code>] [<code>X</code>] [<code>)</code>] [<code>=F7</code>] [<=
code>Y</code>] [<code>2</code>] [<code>(</code>] [<code>X</code>] [<code>)<=
/code>] [<code>STO&#8594;</code>] [<code>X</code>]
<br><img src=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti83/pic/newton93.gif" width=3D"200" =
height=3D"127" alt=3D"first two iterations of Newton=92s Method"></td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Now iterate until the guesses converge.</td>

<td colspan=3D"2" class=3D"ti83step">Both:&nbsp;Each additional [<code>ENTE=
R</code>] keypress computes a further guess.
<br>&nbsp;<br> After just four more iterations, the process has converged.
(If you want, you can press [<code>^</code>] [<code>2</code>] to verify tha=
t
this is indeed the square root of 2.)</td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">&nbsp;</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti8=
3/pic/newton4.gif" width=3D"200" height=3D"136" class=3D"at" alt=3D"next fo=
ur iterations of Newton=92s Method"></td>
<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti83/p=
ic/newton94.gif" width=3D"200" height=3D"127" class=3D"at" alt=3D"next four=
 iterations of Newton=92s Method"></td></tr>

</tbody></table>


<h2 id=3D"Prgm">Method 2: Calculator Program</h2>

<p class=3D"brk">The TI-83/84 and TI-89 are programmed somewhat differently=
.
You can download programs for both calculator families in the file
<a href=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti83/prog/newton.zip">NEWTON.ZIP</a>
(31&nbsp;KB, revised
28&nbsp;Dec&nbsp;2016), or you can key in the
program following the directions below.</p>

<p class=3D"brk">The TI-83/84 program to run Newton=92s Method should work
for any function, even one you don=92t know how to differentiate,
because it computes the derivative numerically. The TI-89 program will
work for any differentiable function, because the TI-89
finds the algebraic derivative for you.</p>

<table class=3D"ti8389proc">

<tbody><tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Create a new program.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;[<code>PRGM</code>] [<code>&#9668;</c=
ode>] [<code>1</code>]</td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;[<code>APPs</code>] [<code>7</code>] [<c=
ode>3</code>]</td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Name the program NEWTON.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;The calculator has put you in alpha m=
ode already. Look for the
<em>green</em> letters above each key and press
[<code>N</code>] [<code>E</code>] [<code>W</code>] [<code>T</code>] [<code>=
O</code>] [<code>N</code>]. Carefully check the screen, and
if necessary back up and make corrections. Press
[<code>ENTER</code>].</td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;Press [<code>&#9660;</code>] [<code>&#96=
60;</code>] to get to the
program name screen.
The calculator has put you in alpha mode already. Look for the
<em>purple</em> letters above each key and press
[<code>N</code>] [<code>E</code>] [<code>W</code>] [<code>T</code>] [<code>=
O</code>] [<code>N</code>]. Carefully check the screen, and
if necessary back up and make corrections. Press
[<code>ENTER</code>].</td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Enter this program, adapted from Larson-Hostetle=
r-Edwards
<cite>Calculus</cite> 6/e.
(Check your calculator manual if you need help.)
<br>&nbsp;<br><strong class=3D"key">Special notes for the TI-89 program:</s=
trong>
<ul><li>The =93d=94 in the first line of the Loop is the
Differentate function from the Calc menu.</li>
<li>The Exact/Approx mode is saved, set to Approximate, and restored.
That way <span id=3D"U20201116b">you don=92t have to remember to</span> ent=
er =931.=94</li></ul></td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;<pre id=3D"U20120718a">Disp "INITIAL =
GUESS"
Input X
1&#8594;N
Lbl 1
X-Y1/nDeriv(Y1,X,X)&#8594;R
If abs(X-R)&lt;abs(X/1E10)
Goto 2
R&#8594;X
Disp {X,N}
N+1&#8594;N
Goto 1
Lbl 2
Disp "ROOT=3D",R
Disp "ITER=3D",N
</pre>
After entering and carefully checking the program, press
[<small><code>2nd</code>&nbsp;<code>MODE</code> <i>makes</i></small> <code>=
QUIT</code>] to return to the home screen.</td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;<pre>newton()
Prgm
getMode("Exact/Approx")&#8594;str1
setMode("Exact/Approx","Approximate")
ClrIO
Disp "Initial guess=3D",t
1&#8594;z
Loop
  t-y1(t)/(d(y1(x),x))|x=3Dt&#8594;y
  If abs(t-y)&lt;abs(t/1E10)
    Exit
  z+1&#8594;z
  y&#8594;t
EndLoop
Disp "Root=3D",y
Disp "Iterations=3D",z
setMode("Exact/Approx",str1)
DelVar str1
EndPrgm
</pre>
After entering and carefully checking the program, press
<span id=3D"U20201116c">[<small><code>2nd</code>&nbsp;<code>ESC</code> <i>m=
akes</i></small> <code>QUIT</code>]</span>
to return to the home screen.</td></tr>


</tbody></table>

<p class=3D"brk">Let=92s test the program by finding a solution of
<i>x</i>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;cos(<i>x</i>).
That means finding the positive zero of
<i>f</i>(<i>x</i>)&nbsp;=3D <i>x</i>&nbsp;&#8722;&nbsp;cos(<i>x</i>). We=92=
ll use an
initial guess of 0.</p>

<p class=3D"nonbrk">Make sure the calculator is in radian mode.</p>

<table class=3D"ti8389proc">

<tbody><tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Put the function into Y1.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;[<code>Y=3D</code>]
<br>&nbsp;<br> In Y1, press [<code>x,T,&#952;,n</code>] [<code>&#8722;</cod=
e>] [<code>COS</code>] [<code>x,T,&#952;,n</code>] [<code>)</code>]</td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;[<code>&#9670;</code>] [<code>Y=3D</code=
>]
<br>&nbsp;<br> In Y1, press [<code>X</code>] [<code>&#8722;</code>] [<small=
><code>2nd</code>&nbsp;<code>Z</code> <i>makes</i></small> <code>COS</code>=
]
    [<code>X</code>] [<code>)</code>]</td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Return to the home screen.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;Press [<small><code>2nd</code>&nbsp;<=
code>MODE</code> <i>makes</i></small> <code>QUIT</code>].</td>
<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;Press [<small><code>2nd</code>&nbsp;<cod=
e>ESC</code> <i>makes</i></small> <code>QUIT</code>].</td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">Run the program.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;Press [<code>PRGM</code>], then the n=
umber next to the NEWTON
program. (This number will vary depending on any other programs in
your calculator.) Press [<code>ENTER</code>] to start the program.
<br>&nbsp;<br>You=92re prompted for an initial guess. Enter 0.</td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;
Press [<small><code>2nd</code>&nbsp;<code>&#8722;</code> <i>makes</i></smal=
l> <code>VAR-LINK</code>], scroll to <code>newton</code>, and press
[<code>ENTER</code>]. This pastes <code>newton(</code> to your home screen.
<br>&nbsp;<br>Enter the initial guess, 0, and then [<code>)</code>] [<code>=
ENTER</code>].</td></tr>

<tr><td class=3D"ti83conc">The program finds the answer, about 0.7391, in s=
ix
iterations.</td>

<td class=3D"ti83step">TI-83/84:&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti8=
3/pic/newton5.gif" width=3D"200" height=3D"136" class=3D"at" alt=3D"TI-83/8=
4 Newton=92s Method program results"></td>

<td class=3D"ti89step">TI-89:&nbsp;<img src=3D"https://brownmath.com/ti83/p=
ic/newton95.gif" width=3D"200" height=3D"127" class=3D"at" alt=3D"TI-89 New=
ton=92s Method program results"></td></tr>

</tbody></table>



